# Trademark Policy

Last updated: 2026-07-09

## Reserved names

The following names and identifiers are reserved by the Jardias project
author (Cazlor) for use in referring to the original project and its
official derivatives:

- **Jardias** — primary project name
- **Jarnis** — legacy code name
- **Actor01** — current code name in the repository
- **小明** — example character used in documentation and demos
- **IPU** (Intelligence Primitive Unit / 智能基元) — architectural term
- **Yinao** (义脑) — architectural term
- **Shice** (时策) — architectural term and scheduling system name
- **HEEL** — memory architecture name
- **ACP** (Agent Context Protocol) — protocol name

## What is NOT covered

The Apache License 2.0 (under which the code is licensed) does NOT
grant you any right to use these names. Apache Section 6 explicitly
reserves trademarks for the Licensor.

## Allowed without permission

You may, without prior written permission, use the reserved names in
the following ways:

- **Reference and discussion**: writing articles, blog posts, talks,
  or academic papers that reference Jardias / Actor01 by name.
- **Verbatim forks**: forking the source code on public hosting
  platforms (GitHub, GitLab, etc.) under the project's original name,
  provided that the fork clearly identifies modifications and does
  not imply endorsement by the original project.
- **Compatibility statements**: stating that your product is
  "compatible with Jardias" or "supports the Shice protocol" in
  factual, non-promotional language.

## Requires written permission

The following uses require prior written permission from the project
author:

- **Product or service names**: naming a commercial product,
  SaaS service, or commercial training course after any reserved name
  or using one as a sub-brand.
- **Logo or visual identity**: using project logos or distinctive
  visual marks in merchandise, marketing, or third-party UI.
- **Endorsement implication**: using the names in marketing copy
  in a way that suggests official endorsement or certification by
  the Jardias project.
- **Academic misappropriation**: republishing the papers under
  library/ in a commercial publication without honoring the
  CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 terms (NonCommercial clause and ShareAlike clause).

## Academic citation

The papers in library/ are academic works. Citing them in other
academic work, translating them for non-commercial purposes, or
adapting them into non-commercial derivative papers is encouraged
and falls under the CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license — no additional
trademark permission is required for factual academic use.

## Reporting misuse

If you become aware of uses that may violate this policy, please
open a public issue or contact the project author.

## Changes

This policy may be updated. Material changes will be announced in
the project's release notes and dated above.